sec.p:
With all these limitations kept in mind, this study produced five major findings as follows:


Although a discomfort glare index should have both inherent sub-divisibility and additivity, sub-divisibility is not the same as additivity of glare sensation from common non-uniform glare sources;

UGR, CGI, BGI, and VCP all have valid additivity of glare sensation from multiple discrete non-uniform glare sources presented across a scene, within a range of position indices d = 2.60–7.26, s = 0.03–2.83;

UGR and CGI have valid sub-divisibility of glare sensation, but BGI and VCP do not, within a range of luminaire layout (d = 2.60–7.26, s = 0.03–2.83), which would hinder the adoption of the numerical method at pixel level by BGI and VCP for non-uniform glare assessment;

Current formulae of UGR, CGI, BGI, and VCP, when calculated using the numerical method at pixel level, all overestimate the glare sensation from non-uniform electric light sources that young people with normal acuity and colour vision may feel;

The failure of UGR, CGI, BGI and VCP to predict discomfort glare for real non-uniform light sources is independent of the non-uniformity level of the glaring surfaces.
